âš™ï¸ Step-by-Step: Creating an LVM Setup
ğŸ§© Example setup

Assume you have:

/dev/nvme1n1  â†’ 1 GB disk
/dev/nvme2n1  â†’ 1 GB disk

Goal â†’ Combine both into a single 2 GB logical volume mounted at /mnt/data.

ğŸ§± Step 1: Install LVM tools
sudo apt update
sudo apt install lvm2 -y

ğŸ§­ Step 2: Create Physical Volumes (PVs)
sudo pvcreate /dev/nvme1n1 /dev/nvme2n1


Check:
sudo pvs

ğŸ§° Step 3: Create a Volume Group (VG)
sudo vgcreate vg_data /dev/nvme1n1 /dev/nvme2n1


Check:
sudo vgs

ğŸ“¦ Step 4: Create a Logical Volume (LV)
Use all free space from the VG:
sudo lvcreate -n lv_data -l 100%FREE vg_data


Check:
sudo lvs
ğŸª¶ Step 5: Create a Filesystem on LV
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/vg_data/lv_data

ğŸ—‚ Step 6: Mount the Logical Volume
sudo mkdir /mnt/data
sudo mount /dev/vg_data/lv_data /mnt/data


Check:

df -h | grep data

ğŸ§  Step 7: Make Mount Persistent Across Reboot

Get UUID:
sudo blkid /dev/vg_data/lv_data


Edit /etc/fstab:
sudo nano /etc/fstab


Add this line:

/dev/vg_data/lv_data  /mnt/data  ext4  defaults  0  2


Save and verify:

sudo umount /mnt/data
sudo mount -a
df -h





ğŸš€ Extending an Existing LVM Volume

Suppose you attach a new disk /dev/nvme3n1 (4 GB)
and want to extend /mnt/data from 2 GB â†’ 6 GB.

ğŸ§± Step 1: Create Physical Volume
sudo pvcreate /dev/nvme3n1
sudo pvs

ğŸ§° Step 2: Extend the Volume Group
sudo vgextend vg_data /dev/nvme3n1
sudo vgs

ğŸ“¦ Step 3: Extend the Logical Volume

Option A: Use all free space
sudo lvextend -l +100%FREE /dev/vg_data/lv_data

Option B: Add 2 GB specifically
sudo lvextend -L +2G /dev/vg_data/lv_data


Check:
sudo lvs

ğŸ§  Step 4: Resize Filesystem to Use New Space
For ext4:
sudo resize2fs /dev/vg_data/lv_data

Check:

df -h /mnt/data